<br>
Take the initiative to invite people to your group, do not just be a LFG person.  Get to know the zones where you hunt and raid well, take in that group or raid and lay waste to everything.  A good warrior should not only be able to call the shots in a given zone, but pull that zone.  I do not care if it is hateplane or HoT, you can pull those zones as good as any monk.  The key is knowledge.  The warrior behind the keyboard is much more important than any armor you can wear or weapons you can wield.<br>
<br>
Furor is not a great warrior because of what he wears.  Furor is a great warrior because he went into the unknown leading others, and using what he learned formed strategies that got all his friends and family back home alive.  Loot is simply a by-product of that.<br>
<br>
Best of luck, and be a LEADER.<br>
<br>
Bayho <p>Loyalty above all, except Honor.</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2F2F4F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/uscarsoulklaw.showPublicProfile?language=EN>ScarSoulKlaw</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>knows that Warriors are Superior</span><br>  Posts: 17<br> <font color=#FF0000>(6/20/02 9:13:36 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthebattlefield.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=950.topic&index=26>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: what makes a good warrior?</span><hr size=1> This is a great thread.  One thing I would like to add is flexibility - in 2 forms.<br>
<br>
The first is leadership/guidance.  Be willing to try things, work with your group and discuss options.  Wins are sweeter and losses don't hurt as bad when everyone has a hand in it.<br>
<br>
The other is in your equipment choices.  A group has people go LD or leave suddenly that you were counting on to perform a key function.  Now what do you do?  You grab the item from your bag that helps replace the skills you just lost and encourage the group to understand that with a little assistance you'll all be just fine.<br>
<br>
There are a wide variety of items and techniques a warrior can use to emulate other classes specialty skills - snare, heal, DoT, slow, fear (blinding), stun.  Don't hesitate to keep a few with you.  I carry no less than 7 weapons on me at all times.  As such I can step in for a number of different functions if someone is LOM or OOM and do my best to keep it all together.  Slow, heal, DoT/Snare, Stun and extra bandages are all a proc away.  Sure it's a gamble sometimes but that's what makes the game exciting.  The adventure and teasing lady Luck at the same time as you're taunting the mobs.<br>
<br>
Using these will help to build your knowledge of the other classes and how they view situations.  I have learned a lot from getting tactical ideas from various sources and fitting the pieces together.  It doesn't always work but we almost always come out laughing.  It has also built other players trust in me and my abilites.<br>
<br>
Key points - talk, ask questions if you're not sure about how certain classes work, and try to keep a few surprises in your bag. <p>Scartle SoulKlaw<br>
Dwarven Myrmidon of The Amber Order</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/ubaadan.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Baadan</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.magelo.com/res/eq/itemicon/0011.png" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>knows that Warriors are superior</span><br>  Posts: 150<br> <font color=#FF0000>(7/2/02 7:05:20 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthebattlefield.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=950.topic&index=35>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: what makes a good warrior?</span><hr size=1> I just figured this could use a nice BUMP because it helped me out alot and has some really good info. <p><table  width="40%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
